# 38_objects_set_stroke_width — closes the appearance branch's
# visual loop and the canvas-observable arc's geometry+fill+stroke
# triad.
#
# s239 m1 shipped set_stroke (colour) but the visual outline didn't
# render because fresh-mint Paths default to stroke.width == 0.0.
# m1's trace channel passed clean (stroke == "#0000ff" etc.) but
# the visual half of three-channel acceptance was deferred: a
# black-paint-on-zero-width stroke is invisible to the renderer.
# m2 ships set_stroke_width — first numeric-arg verb on
# ObjectProxy — and the matching stroke_width read query, closing
# the visual loop.
#
# What "closes" means here: a script can now produce a fully-styled
# visible shape on canvas in a single end-to-end sequence:
#
#   objects new "path"
#   objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"
#   objects.p set_fill "red"
#   objects.p set_stroke "blue"
#   objects.p set_stroke_width 4.0
#
# Five lines, four verbs (geometry from s237 m1, fill from s238 m1,
# stroke paint from s239 m1, stroke width from s239 m2), one
# canvas-visible red rect with a blue 4-pixel outline. The arc's
# foundational "scripts can produce visible art on canvas" phase
# is now complete; remaining stroke fields (cap / join / miter /
# opacity) and gradient / swatch bindings stay on the backlog.
#
# Material differences from set_stroke (m1):
#   - Numeric arg, not string token. First numeric-arg verb on
#     ObjectProxy; earlier verbs all took strings or no args. The
#     anon namespace gains arg_as_double (lifted in shape from
#     StylesScriptable / LayersScriptable / GuidesScriptable). It
#     accepts ScriptValue::Double (native) and ScriptValue::Int
#     (coerced via static_cast<double>), so `set_stroke_width 2`
#     and `set_stroke_width 2.0` both reach the same double at
#     the verb seam — matching the user's typical expectation
#     when typing whole-number widths.
#   - Numeric query return. stroke_width is the first numeric
#     ObjectProxy property (others are Int counts or String
#     tokens). Returns ScriptValue::real(node->stroke.width).
#     ScriptValue strict-equality has no Int/Double coercion, so
#     the assert RHS literal must be Double-kind: `== 2.0` works,
#     `== 2` does not. Smoke 38 uses Double literals throughout
#     for kind-cleanness.
#   - No clamp / no negative-refusal. Matches
#     StylesScriptable::stroke_width's shipped convention: the
#     model accepts whatever the script supplies; the renderer
#     handles edge cases (zero = no outline; negative zeros out
#     at the Cairo seam). Consistent behaviour across the two
#     scriptables touching node->stroke.width.
#   - Partial binding-clear. set_stroke_width clears bound_style
#     (a width edit is a direct appearance edit that breaks the
#     style binding), but does NOT clear fill_swatch_id or
#     stroke_swatch_id (swatch bindings represent PAINT
#     references; width edits don't touch paint). Same partial-
#     clear convention set_fill and set_stroke established.
#
# Verify-before-assume's SIXTH "fits unmodified" case in a row.
# EditAppearanceCommand's 14-arg constructor takes whole-StrokeStyle
# on both before and after sides; width is a field on StrokeStyle,
# so the existing capture covers width-only edits without
# modification. Three "existing-fits" outcomes in a row this
# session (set_stroke colour, set_stroke fill-axis preservation,
# set_stroke_width).
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and three test objects (a Path for the numeric matrix, a
# Group for the universal-class probe, a second Path for the
# visual-close phase), validates the new surface end-to-end, and
# tears everything back down. Net structural change to the doc:
# zero. Side effects on the undo stack: AddNodeCommand for the
# mints, EditPathCommand for the geometry sets,
# EditAppearanceCommand entries for the set_fill / set_stroke /
# set_stroke_width calls, DeleteObjectCommand pairs for the
# teardown.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 13 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (REGISTRY):                                       → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 2 (DISPATCH — baseline count):                      → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint test_layer, mint `p` as Path,
#            geometry, baseline stroke_width):
#     p type == "path"                                         → 1 assert.
#     p stroke_width == 0.0 (fresh-mint default)              → 1 assert.
#   Phase 4 (SET — Double literal, byte-clean):
#     p stroke_width == 4.0                                    → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (SET — Int coerces to Double via arg_as_double):
#     p stroke_width == 2.0                                    → 1 assert.
#   Phase 6 (SET — zero, explicit no-thickness gesture):
#     p stroke_width == 0.0                                    → 1 assert.
#   Phase 7 (NEGATIVE-VALUE-ACCEPTED — model accepts; renderer
#            zeroes at Cairo seam):
#     p stroke_width == -1.0                                   → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (UNIVERSAL — set_stroke_width on a Group is NOT refused):
#     g type == "group", g stroke_width == 3.0                 → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 9 (VISUAL CLOSE — fill + stroke paint + stroke width
#            on one Path; visible red rect with blue outline):
#     v fill == "#ff0000", v stroke == "#0000ff",
#     v stroke_width == 4.0                                    → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves):
#     found_path type == "path"                                → 1 assert.
#   Phase 11 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 0 + 0 + 2 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 1 + 1 = 13.
#
# ── On the Int-Double coercion (Phase 5) ─────────────────────────────────
#
# The DSL lexer emits bare `2` as ScriptValue::Int and `2.0` as
# ScriptValue::Double — two different kinds. ScriptValue equality
# is strict-kind with no coercion (see ScriptValue.hpp's `equals`).
# So an assert like `assert obj stroke_width == 2` would FAIL even
# if the underlying width is 2.0, because the query returns Double
# and the literal is Int. The smoke side has to be explicit about
# kind.
#
# But the VERB side accepts both — arg_as_double accepts Int and
# coerces via static_cast<double>. So Phase 5 calls `set_stroke_width
# 2` (Int literal), the coercion lands stroke.width = 2.0, the query
# returns Double(2.0), and the assert RHS `== 2.0` (Double literal)
# matches. This phase exercises the coercion specifically — without
# it, callers would have to track whether their width literal needs
# a decimal point or not, which is the kind of fiddly surprise a
# script DSL should absorb.
#
# ── On the negative-value Phase 7 ────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The model accepts negative widths; the renderer zeroes them out
# at the Cairo seam (Cairo's stroke-width is non-negative). So
# `set_stroke_width -1.0` lands -1.0 on the model, the query reads
# it back as -1.0, but the canvas renders no outline. This is the
# same "model accepts whatever; renderer handles edge cases"
# convention StylesScriptable::stroke_width follows — see the
# comment in StylesScriptable.cpp line 498 ("Inspector clamps at
# its UI layer; the model accepts whatever the script supplies").
# Whether to add a non-negative clamp at the script surface is a
# backlog item; consistency with the styles surface wins for now.
#
# ── On the visual-close Phase 9 ──────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This is the canvas-observable arc's payoff phase. The smoke mints
# a second path `v` (separate from `p` to keep the colour/width
# matrix on `p` clean) and sets all three appearance values:
# fill=red, stroke=blue, stroke_width=4.0. The trace asserts each
# value independently; the VISUAL channel is "Scott looks at the
# canvas and sees a red rect with a blue outline." Three-channel
# acceptance for the milestone hinges on this phase's visual
# behaviour. If the trace passes but the canvas shows no outline,
# the milestone has not landed.
#
# Three-channel acceptance for m2 = trace pass (13 asserts) + clean
# build + VISIBLE blue outline around a red rect after Phase 9.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 13 asserts above.
# Visual channel: AFTER Phase 9, the document shows a red 100×100
#   rect at user-origin with a blue 4-pixel outline. This is the
#   complete payoff of the canvas-observable arc.
# Build channel: Scott's compile.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — baseline.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint object count to compare against after
#[sub] teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer, Path, geometry ===
#[sub] Mint a sentinel-named test layer, activate it, mint `p` as a
#[sub] Path, set its geometry. A freshly-minted Path has
#[sub] stroke.width defaulting to 0.0 (SceneNode/StrokeStyle struct
#[sub] default), so the baseline `stroke_width` query returns 0.0
#[sub] — the exact reason m1's set_stroke produced no visible
#[sub] outline. Phase 4 changes that.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_set_stroke_width_smoke_s239_m2"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p to result
objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p stroke_width == 0.0

#[sub] === Phase 4: SET — Double literal byte-clean ===
#[sub] Double-kind literal lands directly on stroke.width without
#[sub] coercion. The query reads it back through ScriptValue::real;
#[sub] the assert's RHS is also a Double literal so the strict-kind
#[sub] equality compares value-on-value.

objects.p set_stroke_width 4.0
assert objects.p stroke_width == 4.0

#[sub] === Phase 5: SET — Int coerces to Double via arg_as_double ===
#[sub] Int-kind literal `2` goes through arg_as_double's static_cast
#[sub] and lands stroke.width = 2.0. The query returns Double(2.0);
#[sub] the assert RHS is `2.0` (Double), so the kind-strict equality
#[sub] matches. Without arg_as_double's Int-coercion, this phase
#[sub] would silently no-op (the fallback would equal width_before
#[sub] = 4.0 from Phase 4) and the assert would catch the breakage.

objects.p set_stroke_width 2
assert objects.p stroke_width == 2.0

#[sub] === Phase 6: SET — zero, the explicit no-thickness gesture ===
#[sub] `set_stroke_width 0.0` is the explicit way for a script to
#[sub] remove a stroke's thickness — distinct from the fresh-mint
#[sub] default (which arrives at 0.0 via the SceneNode struct
#[sub] default, not via the verb). After this phase, the rect's
#[sub] outline disappears even though stroke.paint is still set
#[sub] (the colour from m1's earlier set_stroke calls remains
#[sub] intact — width and paint are orthogonal axes).

objects.p set_stroke_width 0.0
assert objects.p stroke_width == 0.0

#[sub] === Phase 7: NEGATIVE-VALUE-ACCEPTED ===
#[sub] The model accepts negative widths; the renderer zeroes them
#[sub] at the Cairo seam (Cairo stroke-width is non-negative). The
#[sub] trace channel shows -1.0; the visual channel renders no
#[sub] outline (same as Phase 6's zero). This matches
#[sub] StylesScriptable::stroke_width's "model accepts whatever;
#[sub] renderer handles edge cases" convention. The smoke documents
#[sub] the behaviour rather than enforcing a clamp at the script
#[sub] surface; a future clamp decision is a backlog item.

objects.p set_stroke_width -1.0
assert objects.p stroke_width == -1.0

#[sub] === Phase 8: UNIVERSAL — set_stroke_width on a Group is NOT refused ===
#[sub] Same universal posture as set_fill and set_stroke. Appearance
#[sub] lives on every SceneNode subtype, including container types
#[sub] that don't draw a stroked region directly. The model field
#[sub] update lands; the visual effect on the Group depends on the
#[sub] container's render path (style inheritance / per-child
#[sub] effects).

objects new "group"
set g to result
objects.g set_stroke_width 3.0

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g stroke_width == 3.0

#[sub] === Phase 9: VISUAL CLOSE ===
#[sub] The canvas-observable arc's payoff phase. Mint a second Path
#[sub] `v`, set its geometry to a 100×100 rect, then layer all three
#[sub] appearance values: fill=red, stroke=blue, stroke_width=4.0.
#[sub] The trace asserts each value independently; the VISUAL
#[sub] channel — Scott looking at the canvas — shows a RED rect
#[sub] with a BLUE 4-pixel outline. This is the complete payoff of
#[sub] the canvas-observable arc: geometry from s237 m1, fill from
#[sub] s238 m1, stroke paint from s239 m1, stroke width from s239
#[sub] m2 — five lines of script produce a fully-styled visible
#[sub] shape on canvas.

objects new "path"
set v to result
objects.v set_path_data "M 150 0 L 250 0 L 250 100 L 150 100 Z"
objects.v set_fill "red"
objects.v set_stroke "blue"
objects.v set_stroke_width 4.0

assert objects.v fill == "#ff0000"
assert objects.v stroke == "#0000ff"
assert objects.v stroke_width == 4.0

#[sub] === Phase 10: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" still resolves ===
#[sub] Sanity check that the appearance work didn't disturb the iid
#[sub] index. Same shape smokes 36 and 37 used. `p` and `v` are
#[sub] both Paths; first-hit returns one of them.

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 11: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Four mints (test_layer, p, g, v) — four matching deletes.
#[sub] count returns to count_before — round-trip baseline.

objects delete p
objects delete g
objects delete v
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] `objects` still present; no transient proxies registered.

list

#[sub] Done. The s239 m2 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_stroke_width <number>` accepts Double
#[sub]     and Int (Int coerced via arg_as_double's static_cast),
#[sub]     writes the value directly onto SceneNode::stroke.width,
#[sub]     clears bound_style (style binding break), preserves
#[sub]     fill_swatch_id and stroke_swatch_id (paint bindings
#[sub]     don't disturb on a width edit), pushes
#[sub]     EditAppearanceCommand with whole-StrokeStyle before/after
#[sub]     (only width differs).
#[sub]   - `stroke_width` query returns the double directly via
#[sub]     ScriptValue::real. First numeric ObjectProxy property.
#[sub]   - No clamp, no negative refusal — matches
#[sub]     StylesScriptable::stroke_width's convention.
#[sub]   - Universal across SceneNode subtypes.
#[sub]   - The canvas-observable arc's appearance branch CLOSES:
#[sub]     geometry + fill + stroke (paint + width) all addressable
#[sub]     from scripts. A five-line script produces a visible
#[sub]     styled shape on canvas.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 13 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by m2 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - stroke_cap, stroke_join, stroke_miter, stroke_opacity
#[sub]     verbs. Each is a separate vocabulary (enum tokens for
#[sub]     cap/join, numeric for miter/opacity); scope-limited
#[sub]     out of this milestone.
#[sub]   - Gradient tokens on fill or stroke. Same scope-limit as
#[sub]     m1.
#[sub]   - Swatch / style binding via script. Same scope-limit as
#[sub]     m1.
#[sub]   - Whether to align script-side binding-clear with
#[sub]     mutate_appearance's broader convention (both swatch
#[sub]     bindings cleared on ANY appearance edit) — backlog item.
#[sub]   - Non-negative clamp at the script surface for stroke
#[sub]     width — backlog item.
#[sub]   - Undo / redo exercise. Three-channel acceptance for
#[sub]     Scott visually after Phase 9.
